","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1192":"1192","after 1214":"after 1214","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","18 APR 1201":"18 April 1201","1214":"1214","1246":"1246","1201":"1201","1134":"1134","1199":"1199","Standlake, Oxfordshire, England":"Standlake, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Welford, Berkshire, England":"Welford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew de Beauchamp was born about 1160, in Standlake, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William de Beauchamp, was 32 and his mother, Matilda de Limesi, was 28. He married Eva Grey in 1198, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died after 1214, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1160–after 1214":"umbes 1160–pärast 1214","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1165–1242":"1165–1242","1192–1246":"1192–1246","1195–1238":"1195–1238","1199–1230":"1199–1230","1130–1197":"1130–1197","1134–1201":"1134–1201","about 1195":"umbes 1195","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1198":"1198","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1192":"1192","after 1214":"pärast 1214","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","18 APR 1201":"18. aprill 1201","1214":"1214","1246":"1246","1201":"1201","1134":"1134","1199":"1199","Standlake, Oxfordshire, England":"Standlake, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Welford, Berkshire, England":"Welford, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1160–after 1214":"noin 1160–1214 jälkeen","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1165–1242":"1165–1242","1192–1246":"1192–1246","1195–1238"